{"componentChunkName":"component---src-templates-post-template-jsx","path":"/nan-and-infinity-in-java","result":{"data":{"markdownRemark":{"html":"<h1 id=\"nan-and-infinity-in-java\" style=\"position:relative;\"><a href=\"#nan-and-infinity-in-java\" aria-label=\"nan and infinity in java permalink\" class=\"anchor before\"><svg aria-hidden=\"true\" focusable=\"false\" height=\"16\" version=\"1.1\" viewBox=\"0 0 16 16\" width=\"16\"><path fill-rule=\"evenodd\" d=\"M4 9h1v1H4c-1.5 0-3-1.69-3-3.5S2.55 3 4 3h4c1.45 0 3 1.69 3 3.5 0 1.41-.91 2.72-2 3.25V8.59c.58-.45 1-1.27 1-2.09C10 5.22 8.98 4 8 4H4c-.98 0-2 1.22-2 2.5S3 9 4 9zm9-3h-1v1h1c1 0 2 1.22 2 2.5S13.98 12 13 12H9c-.98 0-2-1.22-2-2.5 0-.83.42-1.64 1-2.09V6.25c-1.09.53-2 1.84-2 3.25C6 11.31 7.55 13 9 13h4c1.45 0 3-1.69 3-3.5S14.5 6 13 6z\"></path></svg></a>NaN and Infinity in Java</h1>\n<p>You may be familiar with the fact that you cannot divide an integer with 0 in Java - it yields <code class=\"language-text\">java.lang.ArithmeticException: / by zero</code>.\nBut what happens when we try to do this with floating point numbers.</p>\n<p>Let's give it a try:</p>\n<div class=\"gatsby-highlight\" data-language=\"java\"><pre class=\"language-java\"><code class=\"language-java\"><span class=\"token keyword\">int</span> m <span class=\"token operator\">=</span> <span class=\"token number\">10</span><span class=\"token punctuation\">,</span> n <span class=\"token operator\">=</span> <span class=\"token number\">0</span><span class=\"token punctuation\">;</span>\n\n<span class=\"token class-name\">System</span><span class=\"token punctuation\">.</span>out<span class=\"token punctuation\">.</span><span class=\"token function\">println</span><span class=\"token punctuation\">(</span>m<span class=\"token operator\">/</span>n<span class=\"token punctuation\">)</span><span class=\"token punctuation\">;</span>\n<span class=\"token comment\">// Exception: java.lang.ArithmeticException: / by zero</span>\n\n<span class=\"token keyword\">float</span> a <span class=\"token operator\">=</span> <span class=\"token number\">10.0f</span><span class=\"token punctuation\">,</span> b <span class=\"token operator\">=</span> <span class=\"token number\">0.0f</span><span class=\"token punctuation\">;</span>\n<span class=\"token class-name\">System</span><span class=\"token punctuation\">.</span>out<span class=\"token punctuation\">.</span><span class=\"token function\">println</span><span class=\"token punctuation\">(</span>a<span class=\"token operator\">/</span>b<span class=\"token punctuation\">)</span><span class=\"token punctuation\">;</span>\n<span class=\"token comment\">// Infinity</span></code></pre></div>\n<p>Now that is interesting, we didn't get an exception, but instead, we got something as a result: <code class=\"language-text\">Infinity</code>.</p>\n<p>If we check out the <code class=\"language-text\">Float</code> class, we can see that there are a couple of constants defined in the class:</p>\n<ul>\n<li><code class=\"language-text\">NaN</code> - A constant holding a Not-a-Number (NaN) value of type float.</li>\n<li><code class=\"language-text\">PositiveInfinity</code> - A constant holding the positive infinity of type float.</li>\n<li><code class=\"language-text\">NegativeInfinity</code> - A constant holding the negative infinity of type float.</li>\n</ul>\n<p>What this means is, that some operations in Java may yield values that are not strictly some defined number and behave in a special way.\nFor example, when we're diving by <code class=\"language-text\">0</code>, we usually say that the result is Infinity. In maths, this has a special meaning, in terms that\nInfinity is not a specific number and has a set of rules defined for it. In Java, we can see that there are two types of infinity: positive and negative.</p>\n<p>To get a positive infinity, it means that the result of some operation approaches infinite value, but from the positive side on the number axis - for\nexample if we divide a positive number by 0, we get infinite results but all of them are positive, thus getting positive infinity.\nOn the other hand, if we divide a negative number by 0, we also get infinite results, but all of them are negative, so negative infinity.</p>\n<div class=\"gatsby-highlight\" data-language=\"java\"><pre class=\"language-java\"><code class=\"language-java\"><span class=\"token keyword\">float</span> a <span class=\"token operator\">=</span> <span class=\"token number\">1.0f</span><span class=\"token punctuation\">;</span>\n<span class=\"token keyword\">float</span> b <span class=\"token operator\">=</span> <span class=\"token number\">0.0f</span><span class=\"token punctuation\">;</span>\n\n<span class=\"token class-name\">System</span><span class=\"token punctuation\">.</span>out<span class=\"token punctuation\">.</span><span class=\"token function\">println</span><span class=\"token punctuation\">(</span><span class=\"token punctuation\">(</span>a<span class=\"token operator\">/</span>b<span class=\"token punctuation\">)</span> <span class=\"token operator\">==</span> <span class=\"token class-name\">Float</span><span class=\"token punctuation\">.</span>POSITIVE_INFINITY<span class=\"token punctuation\">)</span><span class=\"token punctuation\">;</span>\n<span class=\"token comment\">// true</span>\n\n<span class=\"token comment\">// if a is negative</span>\na <span class=\"token operator\">=</span> <span class=\"token operator\">-</span><span class=\"token number\">1.0f</span><span class=\"token punctuation\">;</span>\n<span class=\"token class-name\">System</span><span class=\"token punctuation\">.</span>out<span class=\"token punctuation\">.</span><span class=\"token function\">println</span><span class=\"token punctuation\">(</span><span class=\"token punctuation\">(</span>a<span class=\"token operator\">/</span>b<span class=\"token punctuation\">)</span> <span class=\"token operator\">==</span> <span class=\"token class-name\">Float</span><span class=\"token punctuation\">.</span>POSITIVE_INFINITY<span class=\"token punctuation\">)</span><span class=\"token punctuation\">;</span>\n<span class=\"token comment\">// false, we should be getting negative infinity</span>\n\n<span class=\"token class-name\">System</span><span class=\"token punctuation\">.</span>out<span class=\"token punctuation\">.</span><span class=\"token function\">println</span><span class=\"token punctuation\">(</span><span class=\"token punctuation\">(</span>a<span class=\"token operator\">/</span>b<span class=\"token punctuation\">)</span> <span class=\"token operator\">==</span> <span class=\"token class-name\">Float</span><span class=\"token punctuation\">.</span>NEGATIVE_INFINITY<span class=\"token punctuation\">)</span><span class=\"token punctuation\">;</span>\n<span class=\"token comment\">// true</span></code></pre></div>\n<p>But what happens when both of the numbers are <code class=\"language-text\">0</code>? In maths, dividing zero by zero yields an undefined result.</p>\n<p>In Java we get <code class=\"language-text\">NaN</code>. This is also a constant defined in <code class=\"language-text\">Float</code> and <code class=\"language-text\">Double</code> classes.\nIf we try to divide zero by zero, we get something that is not a number, so <code class=\"language-text\">NaN</code>.</p>\n<div class=\"gatsby-highlight\" data-language=\"java\"><pre class=\"language-java\"><code class=\"language-java\"><span class=\"token keyword\">float</span> a <span class=\"token operator\">=</span> <span class=\"token number\">0.0f</span><span class=\"token punctuation\">;</span>\n<span class=\"token keyword\">float</span> b <span class=\"token operator\">=</span> <span class=\"token number\">0.0f</span><span class=\"token punctuation\">;</span>\n<span class=\"token class-name\">Float</span> c <span class=\"token operator\">=</span> a<span class=\"token operator\">/</span>b<span class=\"token punctuation\">;</span>\n\n<span class=\"token class-name\">System</span><span class=\"token punctuation\">.</span>out<span class=\"token punctuation\">.</span><span class=\"token function\">println</span><span class=\"token punctuation\">(</span>c<span class=\"token punctuation\">)</span><span class=\"token punctuation\">;</span>\n<span class=\"token comment\">// NaN</span>\n<span class=\"token class-name\">System</span><span class=\"token punctuation\">.</span>out<span class=\"token punctuation\">.</span><span class=\"token function\">println</span><span class=\"token punctuation\">(</span>c <span class=\"token operator\">==</span> <span class=\"token class-name\">Float<span class=\"token punctuation\">.</span>NaN</span><span class=\"token punctuation\">)</span><span class=\"token punctuation\">;</span>\n<span class=\"token comment\">// false</span>\n<span class=\"token class-name\">System</span><span class=\"token punctuation\">.</span>out<span class=\"token punctuation\">.</span><span class=\"token function\">println</span><span class=\"token punctuation\">(</span>c<span class=\"token punctuation\">.</span><span class=\"token function\">isNaN</span><span class=\"token punctuation\">(</span><span class=\"token punctuation\">)</span><span class=\"token punctuation\">)</span><span class=\"token punctuation\">;</span>\n<span class=\"token comment\">// true</span></code></pre></div>\n<p>Now, this looks weird. Why isn't the result (<code class=\"language-text\">c</code>), which is clearly <code class=\"language-text\">NaN</code>, not equal to that constant?</p>\n<p>This also comes from maths, where we cannot compare two things that are not numbers. We can only compare something that has\na clear definition or has a clear value. NaN denotes a mathematically undefined value, and as such we cannot compare it (similar to <code class=\"language-text\">NULL</code> in <code class=\"language-text\">SQL</code>).</p>\n<p>What we <em>can</em> do, is to check whether whatever we got is undefined (Not-a-Number) by using <code class=\"language-text\">Float.isNaN()</code> method.</p>\n<h2 id=\"some-notes-on-serialization\" style=\"position:relative;\"><a href=\"#some-notes-on-serialization\" aria-label=\"some notes on serialization permalink\" class=\"anchor before\"><svg aria-hidden=\"true\" focusable=\"false\" height=\"16\" version=\"1.1\" viewBox=\"0 0 16 16\" width=\"16\"><path fill-rule=\"evenodd\" d=\"M4 9h1v1H4c-1.5 0-3-1.69-3-3.5S2.55 3 4 3h4c1.45 0 3 1.69 3 3.5 0 1.41-.91 2.72-2 3.25V8.59c.58-.45 1-1.27 1-2.09C10 5.22 8.98 4 8 4H4c-.98 0-2 1.22-2 2.5S3 9 4 9zm9-3h-1v1h1c1 0 2 1.22 2 2.5S13.98 12 13 12H9c-.98 0-2-1.22-2-2.5 0-.83.42-1.64 1-2.09V6.25c-1.09.53-2 1.84-2 3.25C6 11.31 7.55 13 9 13h4c1.45 0 3-1.69 3-3.5S14.5 6 13 6z\"></path></svg></a>Some notes on serialization</h2>\n<p>When serializing special care should be taken to serialize these values properly.\nIf we do naive serialization, we would get an exception:</p>\n<div class=\"gatsby-highlight\" data-language=\"java\"><pre class=\"language-java\"><code class=\"language-java\"><span class=\"token class-name\">Gson</span> gson <span class=\"token operator\">=</span> <span class=\"token keyword\">new</span> <span class=\"token class-name\">Gson</span><span class=\"token punctuation\">(</span><span class=\"token punctuation\">)</span><span class=\"token punctuation\">;</span>\n<span class=\"token class-name\">System</span><span class=\"token punctuation\">.</span>out<span class=\"token punctuation\">.</span><span class=\"token function\">println</span><span class=\"token punctuation\">(</span>gson<span class=\"token punctuation\">.</span><span class=\"token function\">toJson</span><span class=\"token punctuation\">(</span><span class=\"token keyword\">new</span> <span class=\"token class-name\">SomeObject</span><span class=\"token punctuation\">(</span><span class=\"token number\">10.0f</span><span class=\"token operator\">/</span><span class=\"token number\">0.0f</span><span class=\"token punctuation\">)</span><span class=\"token punctuation\">)</span><span class=\"token punctuation\">)</span><span class=\"token punctuation\">;</span>\n<span class=\"token comment\">// Throws an exception: java.lang.IllegalArgumentException: Infinity is not a valid double value as per JSON specification. To override this behavior, use GsonBuilder.serializeSpecialFloatingPointValues() method.</span></code></pre></div>\n<p>By setting the serialization of these values, we get the following:</p>\n<div class=\"gatsby-highlight\" data-language=\"java\"><pre class=\"language-java\"><code class=\"language-java\"><span class=\"token keyword\">public</span> <span class=\"token keyword\">static</span> <span class=\"token keyword\">class</span> <span class=\"token class-name\">SomeObject</span> <span class=\"token punctuation\">{</span>\n    <span class=\"token keyword\">private</span> <span class=\"token keyword\">float</span> value<span class=\"token punctuation\">;</span>\n\n    <span class=\"token keyword\">public</span> <span class=\"token class-name\">SomeObject</span><span class=\"token punctuation\">(</span><span class=\"token keyword\">float</span> value<span class=\"token punctuation\">)</span> <span class=\"token punctuation\">{</span>\n        <span class=\"token keyword\">this</span><span class=\"token punctuation\">.</span>value <span class=\"token operator\">=</span> value<span class=\"token punctuation\">;</span>\n    <span class=\"token punctuation\">}</span>\n\n    <span class=\"token keyword\">public</span> <span class=\"token keyword\">float</span> <span class=\"token function\">getValue</span><span class=\"token punctuation\">(</span><span class=\"token punctuation\">)</span> <span class=\"token punctuation\">{</span>\n        <span class=\"token keyword\">return</span> value<span class=\"token punctuation\">;</span>\n    <span class=\"token punctuation\">}</span>\n\n    <span class=\"token keyword\">public</span> <span class=\"token keyword\">void</span> <span class=\"token function\">setValue</span><span class=\"token punctuation\">(</span><span class=\"token keyword\">float</span> value<span class=\"token punctuation\">)</span> <span class=\"token punctuation\">{</span>\n        <span class=\"token keyword\">this</span><span class=\"token punctuation\">.</span>value <span class=\"token operator\">=</span> value<span class=\"token punctuation\">;</span>\n    <span class=\"token punctuation\">}</span>\n<span class=\"token punctuation\">}</span>\n\n<span class=\"token punctuation\">.</span><span class=\"token punctuation\">.</span><span class=\"token punctuation\">.</span>\n\n<span class=\"token class-name\">GsonBuilder</span> builder <span class=\"token operator\">=</span> <span class=\"token keyword\">new</span> <span class=\"token class-name\">GsonBuilder</span><span class=\"token punctuation\">(</span><span class=\"token punctuation\">)</span><span class=\"token punctuation\">;</span>\nbuilder<span class=\"token punctuation\">.</span><span class=\"token function\">serializeSpecialFloatingPointValues</span><span class=\"token punctuation\">(</span><span class=\"token punctuation\">)</span><span class=\"token punctuation\">;</span>\n<span class=\"token class-name\">Gson</span> gson <span class=\"token operator\">=</span> builder<span class=\"token punctuation\">.</span><span class=\"token function\">create</span><span class=\"token punctuation\">(</span><span class=\"token punctuation\">)</span><span class=\"token punctuation\">;</span>\n\n<span class=\"token class-name\">System</span><span class=\"token punctuation\">.</span>out<span class=\"token punctuation\">.</span><span class=\"token function\">println</span><span class=\"token punctuation\">(</span>gson<span class=\"token punctuation\">.</span><span class=\"token function\">toJson</span><span class=\"token punctuation\">(</span><span class=\"token keyword\">new</span> <span class=\"token class-name\">SomeObject</span><span class=\"token punctuation\">(</span><span class=\"token number\">10.0f</span><span class=\"token operator\">/</span><span class=\"token number\">0.0f</span><span class=\"token punctuation\">)</span><span class=\"token punctuation\">)</span><span class=\"token punctuation\">)</span><span class=\"token punctuation\">;</span>\n<span class=\"token comment\">// {\"value\":Infinity}</span>\n\n<span class=\"token class-name\">System</span><span class=\"token punctuation\">.</span>out<span class=\"token punctuation\">.</span><span class=\"token function\">println</span><span class=\"token punctuation\">(</span>gson<span class=\"token punctuation\">.</span><span class=\"token function\">toJson</span><span class=\"token punctuation\">(</span><span class=\"token keyword\">new</span> <span class=\"token class-name\">SomeObject</span><span class=\"token punctuation\">(</span><span class=\"token operator\">-</span><span class=\"token number\">10.0f</span><span class=\"token operator\">/</span><span class=\"token number\">0.0f</span><span class=\"token punctuation\">)</span><span class=\"token punctuation\">)</span><span class=\"token punctuation\">)</span><span class=\"token punctuation\">;</span>\n<span class=\"token comment\">// {\"value\":-Infinity}</span>\n\n<span class=\"token class-name\">System</span><span class=\"token punctuation\">.</span>out<span class=\"token punctuation\">.</span><span class=\"token function\">println</span><span class=\"token punctuation\">(</span>gson<span class=\"token punctuation\">.</span><span class=\"token function\">toJson</span><span class=\"token punctuation\">(</span><span class=\"token keyword\">new</span> <span class=\"token class-name\">SomeObject</span><span class=\"token punctuation\">(</span><span class=\"token number\">0.0f</span><span class=\"token operator\">/</span><span class=\"token number\">0.0f</span><span class=\"token punctuation\">)</span><span class=\"token punctuation\">)</span><span class=\"token punctuation\">)</span><span class=\"token punctuation\">;</span>\n<span class=\"token comment\">// {\"value\":NaN}</span></code></pre></div>\n<p>Be careful though, these values may not be recognized by some JSON parsers and you may get some unpredictable results, such as\nthe values to be converted to <code class=\"language-text\">String</code> or getting an error while parsing.</p>","timeToRead":3,"excerpt":"NaN and Infinity in Java You may be familiar with the fact that you cannot divide an integer with 0 in Java - it yields .\nBut what happens…","frontmatter":{"title":"NaN and Infinity in Java","date":"2020-07-02 18:08:26 +0200","categories":["java"],"tags":["java","nan","infinity","positive-infinity","negative-infinity"],"description":null,"keywords":"java, nan, infinity, positive-infinity, negative-infinity","author":"Pavle Jonoski","cover":{"childImageSharp":{"fixed":{"base64":"data:image/png;base64,","width":204,"height":132,"src":"/static/83761a4ca4c0ee75bf7fec5d84b5ce3f/02521/java.png","srcSet":"/static/83761a4ca4c0ee75bf7fec5d84b5ce3f/02521/java.png 1x"}}}},"fields":{"slug":"/nan-and-infinity-in-java","date":"2020-07-02T16:08:26.000Z"}}},"pageContext":{"slug":"/nan-and-infinity-in-java","nexttitle":"How to increase Travis CI timeout?","nextslug":"/how-to-increase-travis-ci-timeout","prevtitle":"How to convert String to InputStream in Java","prevslug":"/how-to-convert-string-to-inputstream-in-java","tagList":["java","interface","callbacks","asynchronus calls","python","pandas","abstraction","OOP","Class","collection","API","Map","HashMap","LinkedHashMap","TreeMap","Python","cli","args","argparse","javascript","es6","beginner","codenewbie","Primary_key","implementation","Composite_key","language-support","localization","internationalization","linux","file permissions","Project Euler","Algortithms","SQL","database","commands","GO","Datatypes","Variables","Constants","HTML5","Web development","tricks","NumpPy","array","NLP","libraries","text processing","go","golang","data-structure","optimization","java 7","Java 8","comparison","mkdir(make-dir) and rmdir(remove-dir command) command","nodejs","backend","frontend","postgres","mac","installation","games","gamedev","memory","html","bootstrap","web development","data","strings","final","finally","finalize","Git","GitLens","VS Code Extension","CSS","Images","Image Display","CSS Variables","JavaScript","sort","localeCompare","Responsive Fonts","CSS Fonts","default method","static static","plot","spring boot","controller","annotation","mvc","rest","random","List","Set","Queue","hacktoberfest","python3","features","set","hashset","treeset","linkedhashset","list","array list","linked list","vector","slice","delete","one-liner","string","input-stream","nan","infinity","positive-infinity","negative-infinity","ci","travis-ci","travis","type-error","dict","pypi","pypi-stats","modules","python-modules","python-with","with statement","tags","doctype","meta","viewport","meta-tag","git","git-write","git pull","lists","list-index","dictionaries","dict-keys","current-time","millis","milliseconds","c-sharp","c++","scala","kotlin","ruby","php","C","rust","objective-c","dart","lua","haskell","clojure","matlab","octave","R","clickhouse","databases","clickhouse-cli","exceptions","linux-directoy","bin","etc","dev","root","home","lib","sbin","equals","contains","ls","list-command","git-remote","git-checkout","git-branches","mysql","mariadb","github","github-pages","revert","git-revert","git-reset","git-rebase","regex","windows","pip","pytorch","conda","psycopg2","postgresql","delete-branch","repository","command-line","github.com"],"categoryList":["java","python","javascript","databases","linux","go","html","other","git","ci"],"latestPostEdges":[{"node":{"fields":{"slug":"/callbacks-in-java"},"frontmatter":{"template":"post","title":"CallBacks in Java","tags":["java","interface","callbacks","asynchronus calls"],"categories":["java"],"date":"2021-03-01 21:53:39 +0600"}}},{"node":{"fields":{"slug":"/pandas-read-files"},"frontmatter":{"template":"post","title":"Pandas read files","tags":["python","pandas"]